Between Aug 2021 and Jan 2022, inflation jumped 2% to 5.6%. Latest figures from Feb put it over 4%. Given underlying factors (energy/fuel and food prices) I would not expect it to have dropped by now. So even with a drop of 2% over the rest of the year, I would expect inflation to be at or just above 4% come December. 80% certainty as the EU has fared relatively well through the inflation spike, and we are in the dark as to the current inflation situation.

After reaching a record rate of 4.6% in the fourth quarter of last year, inflation in the euro area is projected to peak at 4.8% in the first quarter of 2022 and remain above 3% until the third quarter of the year. As the pressures from supply constraints and high energy prices fade, inflation is expected to decline to 2.1% in the final quarter of the year, before moving below the European Central Bank's 2% target throughout 2023. Overall, inflation in the euro area is forecast to increase from 2.6% in 2021 (2.9% in the EU) to 3.5% (3.9% EU) in 2022, before declining to 1.7% (1.9% EU) in 2023.

Historically the EU CPI is in the 2%-ish range, so that's my anchor. But given the inflationary pressures globally + the RUssia/Ukraine crisis (energy price pressures compound the already scarce energy in the EU) I suspect we will see higher-for-longer inflation. That said, we are near historic higher so we will not only see the impact of normalization of inflationary pressures over time but also the base effects kick in, this suggests deflationary drag. Not to mention if we have a "hard landing"" associated with a rising rate cycle.

Quite a tough call. Prices have been rising quickly late 2021, so the annual inflation will take those higher prices into account, but 4% is around what I would expect it to be, so a toss-up for me at the moment.
The correct answer will more than likely be "YES," but I'm not as confident as the crowd (98%).
